{"id": 9383, "date": "2019-05-01T05:00:00", "date_gmt": "2019-05-01T12:00:00", "guid": {"rendered": "http://estreetshuffle.com/?p=9383"}, "modified": "2019-05-01T05:25:26", "modified_gmt": "2019-05-01T12:25:26", "slug": "cover-me-joe-hill", "status": "publish", "type": "post", "link": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/2019/05/01/cover-me-joe-hill/", "title": {"rendered": "Cover Me: Joe Hill"}, "content": {"rendered": "<p>On International Worker&#8217;s Day 2014, Bruce opened his show in Tampa on a sober note with a one-time only performance of the Labor Union anthem, &#8220;I Dreamed I Saw Joe Hill Last Night.&#8221;</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"Bruce Springsteen- &quot;Joe Hill&quot; (Tampa, FL 05/01/14)\" width=\"758\" height=\"426\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/T2UF8yw89yE?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>Bruce&#8217;s performance was a fitting way to honor the occasion. Joe Hill was a leading labor activist and organizer, accused of murder (perhaps falsely, as the song describes) exactly a century before Bruce paid tribute and executed the following year.</p>\n<p>The song itself draws its lyrics from the Alfred Hayes poem by the same name; Earl Robinson turned it into a song in 1936.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"Joe Hill\" width=\"758\" height=\"569\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/5NzdL04GAIk?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>Paul Robeson and Pete Seeger brought the song to a wider audience through their musical and political activism. The newsreel below captures a remarkably clear and powerful performance by Robeson before a group of Scottish miners, and you can feel how much the song means to its audience.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"Paul Robeson sings to Scottish miners (1949)\" width=\"758\" height=\"569\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/B0bezsMVU7c?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>Generation after generation, socially conscious performers have kept the song alive, first Robeson and Seeger, then (famously) Joan Baez at Woodstock:</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"Joan Baez, &quot;Joe Hill&quot; live at the Woodstock Festival, 1969\" width=\"758\" height=\"426\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/l-JW4DKxwQM?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>&#8230;and most recently&#8211;but not finally&#8211;Bruce&#8217;s performance on the High Hopes Tour. The song lives on because the need for it lives on. &#8220;Joe Hill&#8221; remains a powerful reminder of the importance of collective action and fortitude for workers who fight for fairness.</p>\n<p><strong>Joe Hill</strong><br />\n<strong>First performed:</strong> May 1, 2014 (Tampa, FL)<br />\n<strong>Last performed:</strong> May 1, 2014 (Tampa, FL)</p>\n", "protected": false}, "excerpt": {"rendered": "<p>One time only: Bruce acknowledges International Worker&#8217;s Day by opening his High Hopes show in Tampa with a sober performance of &#8220;Joe Hill.&#8221;</p>\n", "protected": false}, "author": 1, "featured_media": 9750, "comment_status": "open", "ping_status": "open", "sticky": false, "template":